  "response": "**Charge:** `Timezone Roulette` (crime_00009, `src/date.ts:29,33`)\n\n**Literal responsible:** `\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\"` at `src/date.ts:29`.\n\nPer the ECMAScript spec, a date-only ISO string (`\"2026-12-20\"` at L33) is parsed as **UTC midnight**, but a date-time string with no offset (`\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\"`) is parsed as **local time**. On the CI server (UTC) the two interpretations coincide, so the test passes; in a European tz (UTC+1/+2) the same literal resolves to an earlier UTC instant, so a \"promo is open\" comparison flips true earlier than intended — opening the window before the calendar day the literal looks like it names.\n\n**Smallest fix:** append `Z` to pin it to UTC:\n\n```diff\n- new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")\n+ new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00Z\")\n```\n\nThat makes the parse deterministic across hosts and reproduces the CI (UTC) behaviour in production without touching the function signature, the `\"2026-12-20\"` literal (already UTC-stable), or any of the downstream half-UTC/half-local reads flagged separately by crime_00003.",
